{"title_page": "Marc Singer", "text_new": "{{For|the filmmaker of the same name|Marc Singer (documentarian)}}\n{{short description|US-Canadian actor}}\n{{BLP sources|date=March 2010}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name= Marc Singer\n| image = Marc Singer at Wondercon (cropped).jpg\n| imagesize = 200px\n| caption =Marc Singer at the 2011 [[WonderCon]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1948|1|29}}\n| birth_place = [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]], Canada\n| death_date =\n| occupation = [[Film]], [[television]], [[theatre|stage]] [[actor]]\n| othername =\n| spouse = [[Haunani Minn]] (until 2014, her death)\n| website = \n}}\n'''Marc Singer''' (born January 29, 1948) is a [[Canadians|Canadian]]-born [[US|American]] [[actor]] best known for his roles in the ''[[The Beastmaster|Beastmaster]]'' film series, as [[Resistance (V franchise)#Michael Donovan|Mike Donovan]] in the original 1980s TV series ''[[V (1983 miniseries)|V]]'', and his role in ''[[Dallas (1978 TV series)|Dallas]]'' as Matt Cantrell.\n\n==Early life==\nSinger was born in [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]] and raised in [[Corpus Christi, Texas]]. He has two brothers (Claude and Gregory) and one sister, [[Lori Singer|Lori]], an actress. His father, [[Jacques Singer]], was a symphony [[conductor (music)|conductor]]; his mother, Leslie (n\u00e9e Wright), a concert [[pianist]]; and his sister, [[Lori Singer|Lori]], is an actress and cellist.\n\n==Career==\nBefore the height of his career, Singer appeared in the [[Roots: The Next Generations|sequel]] to the miniseries ''[[Roots (1977 miniseries)|Roots]]'' as Col. Warner's elder son Andy. He had originally auditioned for the role Jim Warner, but the producers felt he was better suited for the Andy Warner role.\n\nHe found fame in the early '80s with the movie ''[[The Beastmaster]]'' and its sequels, in which he played the title role, and as Mike Donovan in the 1983 miniseries ''[[V (1983 miniseries)|V]]'', the 1984 sequel ''[[V The Final Battle|V: The Final Battle]]'', and the TV series ''[[V (1984 TV series)|V: The Series]].\n\nOther roles include the [[1982 in film|1982]] film ''[[If You Could See What I Hear]]'' (where he portrayed blind musician [[Tom Sullivan (singer)|Tom Sullivan]]), ''[[Body Chemistry (film series)|Body Chemistry]]'', ''[[Something for Joey]]'' (as [[American football|football]] star [[John Cappelletti]]), ''[[Watchers II]]'', ''[[High Desert Kill]]'', ''[[The Fighter (1995 film)|The Fier]]'', ''[[Go Tell the Spartans]]'' and ''[[Dead Space (film)|Dead Space]]'', as well as General Klaus Von Kraut in ''[[A Man Called Sarge]]''.\n\nSinger voiced the character of [[Man-Bat]] on ''[[Batman: The Animated Series]]''. He has guest-starred on television series, such as Barnaby Jones, where he played in the episode titled \u201cTrap Play\u201d(01/07/1975). This is a role he played alongside Nick Nolte in the earlier years.He also appeared in another episode of Barnaby Jones, titled \u201cPrice of Terror\u201d(10/10/75). He also starred as Matt Cantrell in season nine (\"the dream season) of ''[[Dallas (1978 TV series)|Dallas]]''; ''[[The Twilight Zone (1985 TV series)|The Twilight Zone]]''; ''[[The Hitchhiker (TV series)|The Hitchhiker]]''; ''[[Simon & Simon]]''; ''[[Murder, She Wrote]]''; ''[[The Young and the Restless]]''; ''[[The Ray Bradbury Theater]]'' and ''[[Highlander: The Series]]''.\n\nSinger is active in theater and played [[Petruchio]] in the [[American Conservatory Theater]] (A.C.T.) production of [[Shakespeare]]'s ''[[Taming of the Shrew]]'', as well as Christian in ''[[Cyrano de Bergerac (play)|Cyrano de Bergerac]]''. Both ''Taming of the Shrew'' and ''Cyrano'' were filmed.\n\nSinger appeared in the last episode of season 2 of the new version of ''V'', airing on March 15, 2011; however, instead of reprising his role of Mike Donovan, he plays a new character called Lars Tremont. He was in a recurring role as General [[Creature Commandos|Matthew Shrieve]] on [[The CW]] television series [[Arrow (TV series)|''Arrow'']]'s third season.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Blake|first1=Emily|title=Marc Singer joins 'Arrow'|url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2014/12/15/marc-singer-joins-arrow/|website=Entertainment Weekly|publisher=Entertainment Weekly|accessdate=Dec 15, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHis wife was Hawaiian-born actress [[Haunani Minn]]. She died in November 2014.\n\n==Filmography==\n* ''Cyrano de Bergerac'' (TV) (1972) \u2013 Christian de Neuvillette\n* ''Columbo: Double Shock'' (TV) (1973) \u2013 (uncredited) Young TV Doctor\n* ''The Young and the Restless'' (TV series) (1999)\u2013 Chet\n* ''Planet of the Apes'' (TV) (1974) \u2013 Dalton (in episode: # 1.2 \u2013 \"The Gladiators\" \u2013 20 September 1974)\n* ''[[Hawaii Five-O (1968 TV series)|Hawaii Five-O]]'' (TV) (1974) \u2013 Randy (in episode: # 7.5 \u2013 \"Bomb, Bomb, Who's Got the Bomb?\" \u2013 8 October 1974)\n* ''Nakia'' (TV) (1974) \u2013 in episode: # 1.5 \u2013 \"No Place to Hide\" \u2013 19 October 1974\n* ''Things in Their Season'' (TV) (1974) \u2013 Andy Gerlach\n* ''[[Barnaby Jones]]'' (TV) (1975) \u2013 Feather Tanner (in episode: # 3.14 \u2013 \"Trap Play) 7 January 1975)\n* ''Hawaii Five-O'' (TV) (1975) \u2013 Jeff Heywood (in episode: # 8.5 \u2013 \"Target? The Lady\" \u2013 3 October 1975)\n* ''Barnaby Jones'' (TV) (1975) \u2013 Tally Morgan (in episode: # 4.4 \u2013 \"The Price of Terror\" \u2013 10 October 1975)\n* ''Journey from Darkness'' (TV) (1975) \u2013 David Hartman\n* ''Jigsaw John'' (TV) (1976) \u2013 in episode: \"Eclipse\" 29 March 1976)\n* ''The Rookies'' (TV) (1976) \u2013 Blair (in episode: # 4.23 \u2013 \"Journey to Oblivion\" \u2013 30 March)\n* ''The Taming of the Shrew'' (TV) (1976) \u2013 Petruchio\n* ''[[Something for Joey]]'' (TV) (1977) \u2013 John Cappelletti\n* ''Never Con a Killer'' (TV) (1977) \u2013 Tim Donahue... pilot for ''[[The Feather and Father Gang]]''\n* ''[[79 Park Avenue]]'' (mini) TV-Series (1977) \u2013 Ross Savitch\n* ''Visions'' (TV) \u2013 in epi